venue.description: Powell's City of Books is a book lover's paradise, the largest used and new bookstore in the world.

pageInfo.description: The legendary independent bookstore in Portland, Oregon.

items.text: "Powell’s City of Books is the largest independent bookstore in the US. Actually, it's not so impressive when you realize there are only 4 bookstores left in the US." - Conan O'Brien

items.name: Must-see Portland: The Classics
items.description: The best of the Rose City!

items.text: The best selection of sketchbooks and journals I’ve ever seen - all shapes sizes and all kinds of paper!
Studio Ghibli lover? There's an entire section for you right by the cafe. Plenty of plushes, art books, and other collectable goods, in both English and Japanese.

venue.name: Title Wave Used Bookstore

formattedAddress: 216 NE Knott St (btw NE Rodney & NE MLK)

venue.description: Browse through 20,000 used books, audiobooks, CDs, DVDs and magazines at bargain prices, starting at $2 for hardback novels and nonfiction. Some items start at $.25. Discover great selections of children's books and large-print items. Check regularly; the inventory changes every day.

items.text: Booooks! Excited to find this place.
The Title Wave gives a 25% discount to educators on their total purchase at any time.
Classic used bookstore! Great selection. Have new books also
Ask the owner his opinions about things, for some funny snark.
Erudite, eclectic, and exceedingly tended by staff from the best old/new PDX. Another shop has my ultimate loyalty, but this gem and I'd suggest is a better visit than all of downtown.

formattedAddress: 1223 NE M L King Blvd (btw NE Wasco & Multnomah)

items.text: I love this place. Every time i come to PDX I must stop by here if only to walk around and enjoy the vibe!
Great selection, great and kind staff, be sure to check the tables outside for great deals!

items.name: Stuff To See-Do
items.description: Museums, shops, and other misc weird stuff.

items.text: Classic, old school book and publication shop. You might not find anything you want, but it's fun looking.
W ebooks becoming the norm, this will become a museum of ancient artifacts :)
